# Acceptance Test Specification Template

**Purpose:** Document acceptance criteria in executable format (Gherkin/BDD).

**Format:** Gherkin (compatible with Cucumber, JBehave)  
**Best Practice:** One .gherkin file per feature

---

## How to Use

1. **Create file**: `/.spec/acceptance-tests/{feature-name}.gherkin`
2. **Write scenarios** in Gherkin format (Given/When/Then)
3. **Reference specification**: Each scenario maps to acceptance criterion
4. **Execute**: Run with BDD framework or manual test cases

---

## Template Structure

```gherkin
# file: /.spec/acceptance-tests/{feature-name}.gherkin

Feature: [Feature Name]
  As a [role/user]
  I want to [action/capability]
  So that [business benefit]
  
  Related Specification: /.spec/specs/{feature-name}.md

  Background:
    # Setup shared across all scenarios in this feature
    Given [common precondition]
    And [common precondition]

  Scenario: [Scenario Name / Maps to AC-1]
    Given [precondition]
    And [precondition]
    When [user action]
    Then [expected outcome]
    And [additional verification]

  Scenario: [Scenario Name / Maps to AC-2]
    Given [precondition]
    When [user action]
    Then [expected outcome]

  # Outline for parameterized testing
  Scenario Outline: [Parameterized test]
    Given user with <role>
    When <action> is performed
    Then <outcome> occurs
    
    Examples: Valid Cases
      | role  | action | outcome |
      | admin | create | success |
      | user  | create | error   |
```

---

## Example: User Authentication

```gherkin
# file: /.spec/acceptance-tests/user-authentication.gherkin

Feature: User Authentication with JWT
  As an API consumer
  I want to authenticate using username/password
  So that I can access protected resources securely
  
  Related Specification: /.spec/specs/user-authentication.md
  Related Tests: AuthIntegrationTests, LoginServiceTests

  Background:
    # Test data setup
    Given a test user with username "testuser" and password "SecurePass123"
    And the user account is active

  Scenario: AC-1 - Successful login with valid credentials
    """
    Validates FR-1: User Login
    Test: LoginServiceTests.should_returnValidToken_when_credentialsValid()
    """
    Given a user with username "testuser"
    When I submit a login request with password "SecurePass123"
    Then I should receive HTTP 200 OK
    And the response should contain a valid JWT access token
    And the response should contain a refresh token
    And the token should be valid for 1 hour
    And the token should contain my user ID "testuser"
    And the token should contain my role "USER"

  Scenario: AC-2 - Failed login with invalid credentials
    """
    Validates FR-1: User Login error handling
    Test: LoginIntegrationTests.should_reject_invalidCredentials()
    """
    Given a user with username "testuser"
    When I submit a login request with password "WrongPassword"
    Then I should receive HTTP 401 Unauthorized
    And the response should contain error message "Invalid credentials"
    And no JWT token should be returned
    And the failed attempt should be logged

  Scenario: AC-3 - Login attempt with nonexistent user
    """
    Validates FR-1: User Login error handling (edge case)
    Test: LoginIntegrationTests.should_reject_nonexistentUser()
    """
    Given a user with username "nonexistent" does not exist
    When I submit a login request for "nonexistent"
    Then I should receive HTTP 401 Unauthorized
    And the response should not reveal whether user exists

  Scenario: AC-4 - Rate limiting on failed login attempts
    """
    Validates NFR-1: Security - Rate limiting
    Test: RateLimitingTests.should_enforce_loginAttemptLimit()
    """
    Given I have made 4 failed login attempts from IP "192.168.1.1"
    When I submit the 5th login request with wrong password
    Then I should receive HTTP 429 Too Many Requests
    And the response should indicate retry after 60 seconds

  Scenario: AC-5 - Token validation for protected endpoint
    """
    Validates FR-2: Token Validation
    Test: TokenValidationTests.should_accept_validToken()
    """
    Given I have a valid JWT access token
    When I make a request to a protected endpoint with the token
    Then I should receive HTTP 200 OK
    And the protected resource should be returned

  Scenario: AC-6 - Expired token rejection
    """
    Validates FR-2: Token Validation (expired token)
    Test: TokenValidationTests.should_reject_expiredToken()
    """
    Given I have an expired JWT access token
    When I make a request to a protected endpoint with the token
    Then I should receive HTTP 401 Unauthorized
    And the error message should indicate "token expired"

  Scenario: AC-7 - Tampered token rejection
    """
    Validates FR-2: Token Validation (security)
    Test: TokenValidationTests.should_reject_tamperedToken()
    """
    Given I have a valid JWT token
    And I modify the token payload (e.g., change user_id)
    When I make a request with the modified token
    Then I should receive HTTP 401 Unauthorized
    And the error message should indicate "invalid signature"

  Scenario: AC-8 - Token refresh success
    """
    Validates FR-2: Token refresh
    Test: TokenRefreshTests.should_generateNewToken_withValidRefreshToken()
    """
    Given I have a valid refresh token
    When I submit a refresh token request
    Then I should receive HTTP 200 OK
    And a new access token should be returned
    And the new token should be valid for 1 hour
    And the refresh token should remain unchanged

  Scenario: AC-9 - Invalid refresh token rejection
    """
    Validates FR-2: Token refresh error handling
    Test: TokenRefreshTests.should_reject_invalidRefreshToken()
    """
    Given I have an invalid refresh token
    When I submit a refresh token request
    Then I should receive HTTP 401 Unauthorized
    And no new access token should be issued

  Scenario: AC-10 - Role-based access control
    """
    Validates FR-3: Role-Based Access
    Test: AuthorizationTests.should_enforce_roleBasedAccess()
    """
    Given I am logged in as user with role "USER"
    And the endpoint requires role "ADMIN"
    When I make a request to that endpoint
    Then I should receive HTTP 403 Forbidden
    And the response should contain error "Access denied"

  Scenario: AC-11 - Admin access to protected endpoint
    """
    Validates FR-3: Role-Based Access (authorized)
    Test: AuthorizationTests.should_grantAccess_withRequiredRole()
    """
    Given I am logged in as user with role "ADMIN"
    And the endpoint requires role "ADMIN"
    When I make a request to that endpoint
    Then I should receive HTTP 200 OK
    And the protected resource should be returned

  Scenario Outline: AC-12 - Performance targets
    """
    Validates NFR-2: Performance
    Test: PerformanceTests.should_meetResponseTimeTargets()
    """
    When I perform <operation>
    Then the response time should be less than <target_ms> milliseconds for P95
    And the response time should be less than <target_ms_p99> milliseconds for P99

    Examples: Performance Targets
      | operation                | target_ms | target_ms_p99 |
      | Login                    | 100       | 200           |
      | Token validation         | 5         | 10            |
      | Token refresh            | 50        | 100           |
      | Protected resource access| 100       | 200           |

  Scenario: AC-13 - Multiple concurrent login requests
    """
    Validates Scalability: Handle 1000 req/sec
    Test: LoadTests.should_handle_concurrentLogins()
    """
    Given 1000 concurrent users attempting login
    When all requests are submitted simultaneously
    Then all should complete within 100ms (P95)
    And success rate should be > 99%
    And no deadlocks should occur

  Scenario: AC-14 - Login audit trail
    """
    Validates Compliance & Audit
    Test: AuditTests.should_logLoginAttempts()
    """
    Given a user has logged in successfully
    When the audit log is queried
    Then an entry should exist with:
      | Field     | Value    |
      | event     | LOGIN    |
      | username  | testuser |
      | timestamp | [recent] |
      | status    | SUCCESS  |

  Scenario: AC-15 - Failed login audit trail
    """
    Validates Compliance & Audit (error cases)
    Test: AuditTests.should_logFailedLogins()
    """
    Given a user has submitted wrong password
    When the audit log is queried
    Then an entry should exist with:
      | Field     | Value        |
      | event     | LOGIN_FAILED |
      | username  | testuser     |
      | timestamp | [recent]     |
      | ip_address| [user IP]    |
      | status    | FAILED       |
```

---

## Test Execution Mapping

Each scenario should map to:
1. **Specification AC**: AC-1, AC-2, etc.
2. **Code Test Class**: Which JUnit test covers this
3. **Test Method**: Specific `@Test` method

| Scenario | AC | Test Class | Test Method | Status |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Successful login | AC-1 | LoginServiceTests | should_returnValidToken_when_credentialsValid() | ✅ |
| Failed login | AC-2 | LoginIntegrationTests | should_reject_invalidCredentials() | ✅ |
| Rate limiting | AC-4 | RateLimitingTests | should_enforce_loginAttemptLimit() | ✅ |

---

## Best Practices

### DO ✅
- One scenario per acceptance criterion
- Clear Given/When/Then structure
- Use concrete examples, not abstractions
- Make scenarios independent (Background for shared setup)
- Keep scenarios focused (one action, one verification)
- Reference spec and test class

### DON'T ❌
- Test implementation details (input validation belongs in unit tests)
- Create complex scenarios with multiple users and workflows
- Test non-critical happy paths (focus on acceptance criteria)
- Use vague language ("system works correctly")

